organisationRole url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/B143DFC4-584C-454D-919D-D0712EDC026F"><gtr:id>B143DFC4-584C-454D-919D-D0712EDC026F</gtr:id><gtr:name>University of Muenster (Munster)</gtr:name><gtr:address><gtr:line1>University of Muenster</gtr:line1><gtr:line2>Schlossplatz 2</gtr:line2><gtr:region>Outside UK</gtr:region><gtr:country>Germany</gtr:country></gtr:address><gtr:roles><gtr:role><gtr:name>COLLABORATOR</gtr:name></gtr:role></gtr:roles></gtr:organisationRole><gtr:organisationRole url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/7801F008-7C77-45E7-90E9-4345B47D138E"><gtr:id>7801F008-7C77-45E7-90E9-4345B47D138E</gtr:id><gtr:name>University of Plymouth</gtr:name><gtr:address><gtr:line1>Drake Circus</gtr:line1><gtr:line4>Plymouth</gtr:line4><gtr:line5>Devon</gtr:line5><gtr:postCode>PL4 8AA</gtr:postCode><gtr:region>South West</gtr:region><gtr:country>United Kingdom</gtr:country></gtr:address><gtr:roles><gtr:role><gtr:name>COLLABORATOR</gtr:name></gtr:role></gtr:roles></gtr:organisationRole></gtr:organisationRoles><gtr:personRoles><gtr:personRole url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/person/884978D7-147D-41F6-8CEB-CC61285BB2AD"><gtr:id>884978D7-147D-41F6-8CEB-CC61285BB2AD</gtr:id><gtr:firstName>Katrin</gtr:firstName><gtr:surname>Krumbholz</gtr:surname><gtr:roles><gtr:role><gtr:name>PRINCIPAL_INVESTIGATOR</gtr:name></gtr:role></gtr:roles></gtr:personRole></gtr:personRoles><gtr:project url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/projects?ref=MC_U135079245"><gtr:id>579B1E0F-B8E9-43BB-B0A2-C339F2C090A0</gtr:id><gtr:title>Afferent and efferent factors in auditory signal processing</gtr:title><gtr:status>Closed</gtr:status><gtr:grantCategory>Intramural</gtr:grantCategory><gtr:grantReference>MC_U135079245</gtr:grantReference><gtr:abstractText>The ear is usually thought of as sending information about sounds up into to the brain (bottom-up processing). However, the ear is also able to receive information from the brain and modify its function accordingly (top-down modulation). The mechanisms of top-down modulation and its role for hearing are still poorly understood, but is thought that top-down modulation may play a crucial role when listening in noisy environments like a cocktail party. It is conceivable that top-down modulation depends on prior sound exposure or the cognitive state of the listener. The aim of this research strand is to investigate the mechanisms of bottom-up auditory processing and its interplay with top-down modulation. Some of the proposed projects will use modern brain imaging methods to investigate how information about sound features such as musical pitch or sound location is represented in the human brain and how these representations are affected by what we heard previously. Some projects will investigate how top-down modulation affects the function of the inner ear, where sounds are converted into brain signals. These projects will use perceptual experiments and different non-invasive physiological measures to probe inner ear function.</gtr:abstractText><gtr:technicalSummary>Auditory signal processing consists of two stages. At the first stage, which is presumed to occur mainly at sub-cortical levels, the auditory system has to extract the informational components of the incoming signal to process perceptual features, such as pitch, sound location or phonological identity. At the second stage, which occurs at the level of auditory cortex, this pre-processed information has to be represented in a way that makes it accessible to higher-order cognitive processes, such as attentional selection or memory storage. In the auditory system, both the information-extraction and the representational stage of the processing can be influenced by top-down, or efferent information. Understanding afferent auditory signal processing and encoding mechanisms and their interplay with efferent factors is a crucial prerequisite for gaining a better understanding of auditory disability of both peripheral and central origin.

The aim of this research strand is to investigate afferent and efferent factors in auditory signal processing in normal human listeners using both behavioural and non-invasive neuroimaging methods. In one project, perceptual experiments will be used to explore (i) how temporal information is combined across the ears to create the perception of sound source laterality. The results would be expected to have implications for the development of temporal pre-processing strategies in assistive hearing devices. In a second project, we will use electroencephalography (EEG) and high-resolution functional magnetic resonance imaging (fMRI) to investigate the mechanisms by which feature-related information is represented at the level of auditory cortex. In a third project, we will use EEG to investigate how representational information at the level of auditory cortex is affected by contextual effects, such as adaptation. The final project is aimed at investigating the perceptual and physiological consequences of efferent modulation of peripheral auditory function in humans using psychophysical and non-invasive neurophysiological measures (otoacoustic emissions and auditory brainstem responses).</gtr:technicalSummary><gtr:fund><gtr:end>2009-03-31</gtr:end><gtr:funder url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/C008C651-F5B0-4859-A334-5F574AB6B57C"><gtr:id>C008C651-F5B0-4859-A334-5F574AB6B57C</gtr:id><gtr:name>MRC</gtr:name></gtr:funder><gtr:start>2004-04-01</gtr:start><gtr:type>EXPENDITURE_ACTUAL</gtr:type><gtr:valuePounds>390742</gtr:valuePounds></gtr:fund><gtr:output><gtr:artisticAndCreativeProductOutputs/><gtr:collaborationOutputs><gtr:collaborationOutput><gtr:collaboratingOrganisation>University of M?nster</gtr:collaboratingOrganisation><gtr:country>Germany, Federal Republic of</gtr:country><gtr:department>Institute of Experimental Audiology</gtr:department><gtr:description>MEG studies of pitch processing in human auditory cortex</gtr:description><gtr:id>F42073E6-4186-46B6-ADC4